1
00:00:00,190 --> 00:00:01,280
Look important.

2
00:00:01,389 --> 00:00:03,520
It helps you think important.

3
00:00:03,950 --> 00:00:04,719
Rule.

4
00:00:04,830 --> 00:00:07,679
Remember, your appearance talks.

5
00:00:07,870 --> 00:00:10,800
Be sure it says positive things about you.

6
00:00:11,070 --> 00:00:16,480
Never leave home without feeling certain you look like the kind of person you want to be.

7
00:00:16,829 --> 00:00:24,640
The most honest advertisement ever appearing in print is the Dress Right, You Can't Afford Not To slogan,

8
00:00:24,750 --> 00:00:28,879
sponsored by the American Institute of Men's and Boyswear.

9
00:00:29,469 --> 00:00:36,399
This slogan deserves to be framed in every office, restroom, bedroom, and schoolroom in America.

10
00:00:36,590 --> 00:00:39,119
In one ad, a policeman speaks.

11
00:00:39,150 --> 00:00:44,079
He says, you can usually spot a wrong kid just by the way he looks.

12
00:00:44,270 --> 00:00:46,480
Sure, it's unfair, but it's a fact.

13
00:00:46,670 --> 00:00:49,679
People today judge a youngster by appearance.

14
00:00:49,790 --> 00:00:55,600
And once they've tabbed a boy, it's tough to change their minds about him, their attitude toward him.

15
00:00:55,790 --> 00:00:56,960
Look at your boy.

16
00:00:57,150 --> 00:01:00,560
Look at him through his teacher's eyes, your neighbor's eyes.

17
00:01:00,750 --> 00:01:05,519
Could the way he looks, the clothes he wears, give them the wrong impression?

18
00:01:05,710 --> 00:01:10,480
Are you making sure he looks right, dresses right, everywhere he goes?

19
00:01:11,550 --> 00:01:18,480
This advertisement, of course, refers primarily to children, but it can be applied to adults as well.

20
00:01:18,829 --> 00:01:25,920
In the sentence beginning with look, substitute the word yourself for him, your for his,

21
00:01:26,189 --> 00:01:32,079
superiors for teachers, and associates for neighbors, and repeat the sentence.

22
00:01:32,270 --> 00:01:36,799
Look at yourself through your superior's eyes, your associate's eyes.

23
00:01:37,469 --> 00:01:39,840
It costs so little to be neat.

24
00:01:39,950 --> 00:01:41,680
Take the slogan literally.

25
00:01:41,790 --> 00:01:45,840
Interpret it to say, dress right, it always pays.

26
00:01:45,950 --> 00:01:50,799
Remember, look important because it helps you to think important.

27
00:01:51,950 --> 00:01:56,240
Use clothing as a tool to lift your spirits, build confidence.

28
00:01:56,430 --> 00:02:04,640
An old psychology professor of mine used to give this advice to students on last-minute preparations for final examinations.

29
00:02:04,990 --> 00:02:07,280
Dress up for this important exam.

30
00:02:07,310 --> 00:02:08,319
Get a new tie.

31
00:02:08,429 --> 00:02:09,759
Have your suit pressed.

32
00:02:09,759 --> 00:02:10,960
Shine your shoes.

33
00:02:11,149 --> 00:02:14,560
Look sharp because it will help you think sharp.

34
00:02:15,870 --> 00:02:18,400
The professor knew his psychology.

35
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:20,000
Make no mistake about it.

36
00:02:20,189 --> 00:02:24,000
Your physical exterior affects your mental interior.

37
00:02:24,189 --> 00:02:29,439
How you look on the outside affects how you think and feel on the inside.

38
00:02:30,189 --> 00:02:34,000
All boys, I'm told, go through the hat stage.

39
00:02:34,109 --> 00:02:40,319
That is, they use hats to identify themselves with the person or character they want to be.

40
00:02:41,310 --> 00:02:45,680
I will always remember a hat incident with my own son, Davey.

41
00:02:45,870 --> 00:02:51,759
One day, he was dead set on being the Lone Ranger, but he had no Lone Ranger hat.

42
00:02:52,109 --> 00:02:55,200
I tried to persuade him to substitute another.

43
00:02:55,310 --> 00:03:01,360
His protest was, but Dad, I can't think like the Lone Ranger without a Lone Ranger hat.

44
00:03:01,870 --> 00:03:05,120
I gave in finally and bought him the hat he needed.

45
00:03:05,229 --> 00:03:09,360
Sure enough, donning the hat, he was the Lone Ranger.

46
00:03:09,949 --> 00:03:16,159
I often recall that incident because it says so much about the effect of appearance on thinking.

47
00:03:16,509 --> 00:03:23,599
Anyone who has ever served in the army knows a soldier feels and thinks like a soldier when he is in uniform.

48
00:03:23,949 --> 00:03:28,719
A woman feels more like going to a party when she is dressed for a party.

49
00:03:29,389 --> 00:03:35,439
By the same token, an executive feels more like an executive when he is dressed like one.

50
00:03:35,870 --> 00:03:38,400
A salesman expressed it to me this way.

51
00:03:38,669 --> 00:03:43,360
I can't feel prosperous, and I have to if I am going to make big sales,

52
00:03:43,389 --> 00:03:45,680
unless I know I look that way.

53
00:03:46,509 --> 00:03:50,640
Your appearance talks to you, but it also talks to others.

54
00:03:50,750 --> 00:03:53,200
It helps determine what others think of you.

55
00:03:53,469 --> 00:03:59,280
In theory, it's pleasant to hear that people should look at a man's intellect, not his clothes.

56
00:03:59,549 --> 00:04:01,120
But don't be misled.

57
00:04:01,150 --> 00:04:04,879
People do evaluate you on the basis of your appearance.

58
00:04:05,229 --> 00:04:12,159
Your appearance is the first basis for evaluation other people have, and first impressions last,

59
00:04:12,269 --> 00:04:15,840
out of all proportion to the time it takes to form them.

60
00:04:16,509 --> 00:04:22,959
In a supermarket one day, I noticed one table of seedless grapes marked 15 cents a pound.

61
00:04:23,149 --> 00:04:33,360
On another table were what appeared to be identical grapes, this time packaged in polyethylene bags and marked 2 pounds for 35 cents.

62
00:04:33,790 --> 00:04:44,000
I asked the young fellow at the weighing station, what's the difference between the grapes priced at 15 cents a pound and those priced at 2 pounds for 35 cents?

63
00:04:44,509 --> 00:04:47,519
The difference, he answered, is polyethylene.

64
00:04:47,629 --> 00:04:51,680
We sell about twice as many of the grapes in the polyethylene bags.

65
00:04:51,790 --> 00:04:53,280
They look better that way.
